d":"Rainham, Haldimand, Upper Canada, British Colonial America","Rainham, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England"},"en":{"1261–28 November 1327":"1261–28 November 1327","1261–1327":"1261–1327","1261–1346":"1261–1346","1265–Female":"1265–Deceased","1281–1316":"1281–1316","1294–1335":"1294–1335","1240–1283":"1240–1283","–Female":"Deceased","28 November 1327":"28 November 1327","1240":"1240","1261":"1261","1283":"1283","1294":"1294","1281":"1281","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","ABT 1285":"about 1285","after 1316":"after 1316","1335":"1335","1346":"1346","1265":"1265","1317":"1317","Ingoldthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Hockwold cum Wilton, King's Lynn, Norfolk, England":"Hockwold cum Wilton, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Rainham,Norfolk,England":"Rainham, Haldimand, Upper Canada, British Colonial America","Rainham, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"IV","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":29,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":54,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Thomas IV Ingoldesthorpe Knight was born in 1261, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom as the son of Sir John Ingoldesthorpe I and End of line. He married Joan DE BEAUFOY about 1285. He died on 28 November 1327, in Norfolk, England, at the age of 66."},"et":{"1261–28 November 1327":"1261–28. november 1327","1261–1327":"1261–1327","1261–1346":"1261–1346","1265–Female":"1265–Surnud","1281–1316":"1